light-realm." Similarly, Epiphanius of Salamis in the Panarion (Chapters 26 and 36) describes the practices of the Phibionites and Heracleonites. These Gnostics anointed their dying with oil and water, reciting formulas designed to render the ascending soul invisible to the planetary rulers, effectively blindfolding the Archons of the Heimarmene (cosmic fate).Gregory of Nyssa and the Death Prayer of Saint MacrinaA highly significant, non-Gnostic equivalent of a transition liturgy is preserved in Gregory of Nyssa's Life of Macrina (c. 380 CE). On her deathbed, Saint Macrina recites a precise, highly structured prayer (Επιθανάτια Προσευχή της αγίας Μακρίνας) that functions as an afterlife navigation guide :"Εσύ, Κύριε, διέλυσες τον φόβο μας για το θάνατο... Άφησε με να αναπαυτώ... μη έχοντας κάποια κηλίδα ή ζαρωματιά στην μορφή της ψυχής μου, αλλά χωρίς ψεγάδι και κηλίδα να προσφερθεί η ψυχή μου στα χέρια σου..." This prayer represents a transitional theology where the soul actively appeals to God to dissolve the fear of death, protect it from the fiery accusations of the chthonic accusers (the "burning coal" of the adversary), and ensure safe passage into the divine presence.Sacerdotal Degradation: The Sacrament of UnctionThe Catholic sacrament of Extreme Unction (traditionally known as the Last Rites) represents a highly sanitized, simplified, and institutionalized remnant of these original active Gnostic transit rituals. What was originally an active, knowledge-based (gnosis) self-defense manual for navigating a hostile cosmos was transformed into a passive, penitential ritual designed to secure administrative forgiveness of sins prior to death.This shift occurred in 416 CE, when Pope Innocent I, in his Epistula ad Decentium (Letter 25), ruled that the anointing of the sick (based on James 5:14–15) was a formal sacrament reserved exclusively for the institutional priesthood to administer. The active metaphysical defense-shields—such as the blinding of the Archons, 